00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:25.900
I had a question.

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:28.210
Obviously, the
music industry has

00:40:28.210 --> 00:40:31.370
evolved since you've been
doing what you're doing.

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:33.370
What kind of questions
or advice do you

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:37.198
give to artists who are kind
of starting their careers now?

00:40:37.198 --> 00:40:38.740
And what are the
different challenges

00:40:38.740 --> 00:40:43.538
that you think they face to
when you were breaking through?

00:40:43.538 --> 00:40:45.580
KELLY JONES: I don't think
I'd want to start now.

00:40:45.580 --> 00:40:51.940
I think it's much harder for
young musicians to develop,

00:40:51.940 --> 00:40:53.950
because I think there's
so many stats involved.

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:59.557
I think record companies and
management companies, and all--

00:40:59.557 --> 00:41:01.390
not to put them in a
bad light-- but there's

00:41:01.390 --> 00:41:03.640
a lot of statistics
people follow now more

00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:05.860
than when we were starting out.

00:41:05.860 --> 00:41:07.720
For example, what
they did with us was,

00:41:07.720 --> 00:41:09.370
they wouldn't let
us play in London.

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:11.080
They made us avoid London.

00:41:11.080 --> 00:41:13.090
So we'd have to play in
Newcastle, and Scotland,

00:41:13.090 --> 00:41:16.540
and Wales, and build
a proper fan base.

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:19.750
And do 15 interviews a
day in every university.

00:41:19.750 --> 00:41:24.460
So by the time the media caught
up with us, we were actually--

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:25.720
we had a real fan base.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:27.490
So if the media kind
of turned on us,

00:41:27.490 --> 00:41:29.490
or the record wasn't
successful, then we already

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:31.585
had a grounding.

00:41:31.585 --> 00:41:33.460
So the only thing, my
advice would be really,

00:41:33.460 --> 00:41:35.950
I think it still
stems back to the fact

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:38.860
the songs have to work, because
now it's a bit like the '50s.

00:41:38.860 --> 00:41:40.847
The song is more
important than the album

00:41:40.847 --> 00:41:43.180
really, because people are
just downloading or streaming

00:41:43.180 --> 00:41:44.380
one song.

00:41:44.380 --> 00:41:45.810
And if that song
is not very good,

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:48.185
then people are not really
going to listen to you at all.

00:41:48.185 --> 00:41:50.602
So I think it'll always come
back to the songwriting craft

00:41:50.602 --> 00:41:52.140
really.

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:53.770
GETHIN JONES: You've
been quite open,

00:41:53.770 --> 00:41:56.570
as well, about the TV
shows now, in terms

00:41:56.570 --> 00:41:59.890
of the manufactured bands,
with "X Factor," "The Voice,"

00:41:59.890 --> 00:42:01.720
et cetera.

00:42:01.720 --> 00:42:04.420
That's not really something
you ever advocated, is it?

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:05.878
It's not something
you're a fan of.

00:42:05.878 --> 00:42:08.560
KELLY JONES: I don't think it's
something you can judge really.

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:12.100
I have been asked to
judge on all those shows.

00:42:12.100 --> 00:42:13.410
And I'm not against the shows.

00:42:13.410 --> 00:42:15.160
I think they're great
Saturday night tele.

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:17.310
Sat down with the kids when
there would be younger,

00:42:17.310 --> 00:42:19.630
and watching, have a
laugh and all that.

00:42:19.630 --> 00:42:21.990
But I think it's
very hard once you--

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.492
even if you win, to
go on from that point,

00:42:24.492 --> 00:42:26.950
you're always going to be a
contestant winner or something.

00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:29.060
I know some people have
been massively successful.

00:42:29.060 --> 00:42:32.480
But I the majority
of those people,

00:42:32.480 --> 00:42:37.030
it's a different way to come
into the game, then, really.

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:39.163
I think you have
to play in a club

00:42:39.163 --> 00:42:41.080
where there's only three
people that know you.

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:43.363
You have to know what it
feels like to die on stage.

00:42:43.363 --> 00:42:45.280
You have to feel like I
don't want to walk out

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:46.300
the dressing room
because I'm embarrassed

00:42:46.300 --> 00:42:47.455
how crap I was tonight.

00:42:47.455 --> 00:42:49.890
And unless you have
those feelings,

00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:51.050
then you're not going to--

00:42:51.050 --> 00:42:53.310
you can't learn by walking
into a football stadium.

00:42:53.310 --> 00:42:55.450
You have to learn that
from the ground up.

00:42:55.450 --> 00:42:58.540
And that's no different,
I think, from any trade.

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:00.390
You have to make your
mistakes yourself,

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:01.932
you have to walk
into your own walls.

00:43:01.932 --> 00:43:04.758
Otherwise, you're
not really going to--

00:43:04.758 --> 00:43:07.050
one, you're not going to
appreciate it when you get it.

00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:08.730
And it's a bit like
a lottery winner.

00:43:08.730 --> 00:43:11.600
You give a lottery
winner 10 million quid,

00:43:11.600 --> 00:43:14.610
you guaranteed 99%
of them mess it up.

00:43:14.610 --> 00:43:16.560
If you earn the
money, then somehow

00:43:16.560 --> 00:43:17.727
you know what to do with it.

00:43:17.727 --> 00:43:19.685
GETHIN JONES: It is
massive exposure, isn't it?

00:43:19.685 --> 00:43:21.320
We were chatting
about the 18-year-old

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:22.903
