00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:51.150
outside of music, that
you do, that helps

00:44:51.150 --> 00:44:54.192
boost your creativity.

00:44:54.192 --> 00:44:56.400
KELLY JONES: I guess I've
always took my inspiration,

00:44:56.400 --> 00:45:00.720
from for good or for bad, from
whatever I'm going through

00:45:00.720 --> 00:45:03.780
in my own life, on my,
if you want to call it

00:45:03.780 --> 00:45:04.860
a journey through life.

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:07.800
When I started doing it,
I was like 12 years old.

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:09.870
When I started writing
songs I was 18.

00:45:09.870 --> 00:45:11.670
And the 18-year-old
version of me,

00:45:11.670 --> 00:45:16.960
compared to 44 version of me
is very different, I hope.

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:18.792
And there's lots of
mistakes I've made,

00:45:18.792 --> 00:45:21.000
and lots of things I've
done, which are good and bad,

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:21.970
and all the rest of it.

00:45:21.970 --> 00:45:24.680
And you have to deal with
it in different ways.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:27.900
So I think it's, for
me, personally, it's

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:30.150
like a manifestation
of stuff that's

00:45:30.150 --> 00:45:33.392
inside me that has to come out.

00:45:33.392 --> 00:45:35.100
But when it comes to
song mix, and music,

00:45:35.100 --> 00:45:36.750
and all that sort of
stuff, I take inspiration

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:37.417
from everything.

00:45:37.417 --> 00:45:43.350
I listen to lots of stuff from
films, actually, sometimes.

00:45:43.350 --> 00:45:45.340
I mean, when I was
younger, a lot of it

00:45:45.340 --> 00:45:47.323
was conversations, a
lot of people talking,

00:45:47.323 --> 00:45:49.740
and I would take things from
conversations, like literally

00:45:49.740 --> 00:45:50.940
live actual conversations.

00:45:50.940 --> 00:45:53.650
And kind of turn them into
songs and stuff like that.

00:45:53.650 --> 00:45:55.200
And then people would come up
to me in the workman's club

00:45:55.200 --> 00:45:57.150
when I'd go home, and start
telling me their life story

00:45:57.150 --> 00:45:58.500
hoping I would put into a song.

00:45:58.500 --> 00:46:00.720
But start the conversation
with, don't put this

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:02.225
into a song, but--

00:46:02.225 --> 00:46:03.600
and then they
would tell me that.

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:06.710
So that happens a
lot, happened a lot.

00:46:06.710 --> 00:46:08.460
GETHIN JONES: It's
true, though, isn't it?

00:46:08.460 --> 00:46:10.550
You're not allowed to
fail anymore, especially--

00:46:10.550 --> 00:46:11.300
KELLY JONES: Yeah.

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:11.950
GETHIN JONES: --media.

00:46:11.950 --> 00:46:13.810
And I suppose Google's
really good for it,

00:46:13.810 --> 00:46:15.430
because you were
able to establish,

00:46:15.430 --> 00:46:17.820
and so are you--
you're allowed to fail.

00:46:17.820 --> 00:46:19.730
And if you don't fail,
how do you learn?

00:46:19.730 --> 00:46:19.940
KELLY JONES: Yeah.

00:46:19.940 --> 00:46:21.000
GETHIN JONES: [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:22.167
KELLY JONES: Well, I think--

00:46:22.167 --> 00:46:25.110
no, I think you have to--

00:46:25.110 --> 00:46:27.360
going back to when, like we
did that David Bowie tour,

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:29.100
we watched him do a
different show every night.

00:46:29.100 --> 00:46:30.558
When he's in middle
America, he was

00:46:30.558 --> 00:46:32.280
doing a very different
show, to where

00:46:32.280 --> 00:46:33.988
he's doing when he
was on the east coast,

00:46:33.988 --> 00:46:35.510
and like New York, and stuff.

00:46:35.510 --> 00:46:36.960
And I learned a lot
from that, because he's

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:39.293
catering to different people
in different walks of life.

00:46:39.293 --> 00:46:42.780
And you can be indulgent and
selfish, but at the same time,

00:46:42.780 --> 00:46:45.800
you can be very smart
how you do that.

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:47.175
And you do have
to make mistakes.

00:46:47.175 --> 00:46:49.740
Not every record you make
is going to be successful.

00:46:49.740 --> 00:46:52.322
And if you don't do the
mistake, then you've

00:46:52.322 --> 00:46:54.280
got nothing to come back
from each time either.

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:56.070
So it's trial and error, really.

00:46:56.070 --> 00:46:57.140
I mean, you don't know.

00:46:57.140 --> 00:46:59.130
And it's in so many
different people's hands

00:46:59.130 --> 00:47:00.420
when you hand it over.

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:01.980
Some songs you
feel very personal.

00:47:01.980 --> 00:47:03.210
You think people
will connect to.

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:03.710
They don't.

00:47:03.710 --> 00:47:06.760
And other times, you just throw
it away, and people love it.

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.551
It's a very odd thing, really.

00:47:08.551 --> 00:47:09.343
GETHIN JONES: Yeah.

00:47:09.343 --> 00:47:12.180
I think that's probably--
oh, we should do one more.

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:13.013
Yeah, I don't know--

00:47:13.013 --> 00:47:15.555
Craig will probably really kick
me off when we have to leave.

00:47:15.555 --> 00:47:16.200
Hello.

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:17.780
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank you so much.

00:47:17.780 --> 00:47:20.670
I've really enjoyed
this conversation.

00:47:20.670 --> 00:47:23.370
And I love how we've spoken a
lot about you being a family

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:26.280
man and about having drive.

00:47:26.280 --> 00:47:29.070
And I just wanted to
know, being so successful,

00:47:29.070 --> 00:47:31.680
how are you able to impart
this on your children?

00:47:31.680 --> 00:47:36.190
Because obviously they've grown
up with seeing you succeed,

00:47:36.190 --> 00:47:38.870
but they may not necessarily
have seen the back story.

00:47:38.870 --> 00:47:43.470
How do you still
impart the drive?

00:47:43.470 --> 00:47:47.520
KELLY JONES: Well,
I think anybody

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:49.500
that knows me, and knows
me, and knows my kids,

00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:54.120
knows this not really based
around any kind of celebrity

00:47:54.120 --> 00:47:55.530
status or anything like that.

00:47:55.530 --> 00:47:57.270
We don't kind of live like that.

00:47:57.270 --> 00:47:59.050
It's very kind of
grounded upbringing.

00:47:59.050 --> 00:48:00.360
GETHIN JONES: They were
like totally fine with me,

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:00.902
weren't they?

00:48:00.902 --> 00:48:02.341
It was really surprising.

00:48:05.230 --> 00:48:09.810
KELLY JONES: And then,
grounding wise, I guess--

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:11.532
I think all of
this conversation,

00:48:11.532 --> 00:48:12.990
like anything else,
really, I think

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:15.450
the most thing I've
learned in all of life

00:48:15.450 --> 00:48:17.470
really is you have to
be honest with yourself.

00:48:17.470 --> 00:48:20.730
And if you put the most honest
version of yourself out there,

00:48:20.730 --> 00:48:23.197
then it becomes its own success.

00:48:23.197 --> 00:48:24.780
Because you're being
real about stuff.

00:48:24.780 --> 00:48:28.005
And I think with the kids, I've
always been straight with them.

00:48:28.005 --> 00:48:29.880
I've always told them
what they want to know.

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:33.300
And I've always told them
what's going on, really.

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:38.560
And I think even today,
I told them to walk,

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:42.460
to come to see me, to get
the taxi, to come to here.

00:48:42.460 --> 00:48:43.800
And then, they split up.

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:44.620
One called the bus.

00:48:44.620 --> 00:48:46.860
And the whole point of the walk
was to get a bit of fresh air,

00:48:46.860 --> 00:48:47.985
because it was a sunny day.

00:48:47.985 --> 00:48:52.450
So we had a bit of
a moment about that.

00:48:52.450 --> 00:48:54.820
But it was that, but then it
turns into a funny moment.

00:48:54.820 --> 00:48:55.778
Because we have a line.

00:48:55.778 --> 00:48:57.690
We know when they'll
apologize, and I'll

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:58.800
apologize if I'm wrong.

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:00.610
And then we'll have
a crack about it.

00:49:00.610 --> 00:49:04.320
But I think the difference
between my generation growing

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:06.930
up and theirs, is that when
your parents would give you

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:09.810
a bollocking when you were a
kid, and then they'd walk off,

00:49:09.810 --> 00:49:11.500
you didn't quite know why.

00:49:11.500 --> 00:49:14.273
But now, I'll give
them a bollocking,

00:49:14.273 --> 00:49:15.690
but then I'll
explain to them why.

00:49:15.690 --> 00:49:17.646
And then we'll have
a chat about that.

00:49:17.646 --> 00:49:22.230
And look, it's not perfect
by any way or means.

00:49:22.230 --> 00:49:24.447
I've never brought up a
14-year-old girl before,

00:49:24.447 --> 00:49:26.280
or a 12-year-old girl,
or a 3-year-old girl.

00:49:26.280 --> 00:49:27.880
I'm learning how to do it.

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:31.457
So each time it happens,
I'll kick myself to death

00:49:31.457 --> 00:49:33.290
when I go to bed, because
I've messed it up,

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:34.915
or I haven't done it
right or whatever.

00:49:34.915 --> 00:49:37.293
And then my wife
will say, you're

00:49:37.293 --> 00:49:38.960
being ridiculous and
all the rest of it.

00:49:38.960 --> 00:49:40.700
But that's the way I am.

00:49:40.700 --> 00:49:43.568
I over-think pretty
much everything.

00:49:43.568 --> 00:49:46.110
GETHIN JONES: And then write it
down and make loads of money.

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:48.390
KELLY JONES: And then
make a song, yeah.

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:51.830
Write it down, make some money,
and then they take it all.

00:49:51.830 --> 00:49:53.037
It's a funny circle, really.

00:49:53.037 --> 00:49:54.120
GETHIN JONES: Full circle.

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:57.074
Which is probably the perfect
way to finish things off,

00:49:57.074 --> 00:49:58.690
I think.

00:49:58.690 --> 00:49:59.190
I think so.

00:49:59.190 --> 00:50:00.990
Listen, Kelly,
thank you so much.

00:50:00.990 --> 00:50:01.470
KELLY JONES: Cheers, mate.

00:50:01.470 --> 00:50:02.887
GETHIN JONES: Thank
you very much.

00:50:02.887 --> 00:50:04.650
Ladies and gents, Kelly Jones.

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:06.800
[APPLAUSE]

